<HEADLINE>
Child safety seats in unsupported vehicles?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> &quot;OhioGuy&quot; &lt;n...@none.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-07-03T15:53:00 </POSTDATE>
We are getting ready to take a vacation out in Washington and British
Columbia.  Child seats are an issue, because we have two toddlers.
Originally we thought of trying to take our child seats along on the plane,
because sometimes it takes quite a bit of time and effort to figure out a
new child seat.  We assumed we would be using a rental car.  We are using
those $40 round trip airplane tickets for the trip. ($40 includes all taxes
and fees)

However, then I discovered Craigslist, and the fact that Seattle and
Vancouver have thousands of used cars available.  We are also at the point
where we would like a larger vehicle for our growing family - either a van
or station wagon.  The cars out on the West coast usually don't have rust
like they do here, so we are thinking about flying out and getting a used
car that would meet our needs better, then drive back across Canada.

Anyway, this whole thing has made me think about seat belts and child
seats a lot more.

I know that on an older car that doesn't even HAVE seat belts, the law
can't require you to wear them. (since they are, in fact, nonexistent on the
vehicle)

That got me to thinking about other vehicles we have looked at:

1) 1970's camper van - with no seat belts whatsoever other than the front
two seats

2) Cargo van - with no seats at all, except for front two

3) Older vehicle without seat belts, or any way to fasten child safety seat

How does the law apply to these?  My grandpa has one of those 1970's
camper vans, for example.  There is just no way to secure a child safety
seat, but there are plenty of cushioned seats for people to sit on.  Can
they issue a ticket if they see kids without child safety seats, or adults
without seat belts on?

What about a cargo van?  It's obviously safer than riding in the back of a
pickup truck, but again, no sealt belts other than the front two seats, and
no way that I can think of for securing the child safety seats. (maybe there
is a simple way I'm missing?)
</POST>
