Of course, silly, which was why I got on here asking this question.
That's also why I drive slow, very little at night, and I never drink
alcohol.  I also minimize my driving by combining trips, so that I don't
have to do much local driving at all.

However, I don't support the concept of a &quot;nanny state&quot; telling all of us
what to do, any more than I do big brother.  When it comes to this sort of
thing, I'm a libertarian.  I feel that each family should be able to decide
what level of risk they are comfortable with.

I don't think the government should be in the business of telling people
if they can drink, smoke, take drugs, skydive, have sex, what speed they can
drive, etc.  Nor should it be able to tell people they have to wear a
seatbelt if they want to take the risk of not wearing one.  Next thing you
know, they'll be telling the Amish they can't ride horses any more.

The main thing I was mentioning was that some vehicles simply don't have
an easy way at all to add something like a child safety seat.  As such, is
it illegal to drive your kids in it (something like the camper I mentioned)
or simply a bit more dangerous?
