I'd agree except for two things:

1. You're choosing to put your kids at risk, not just yourself.
2. Us taxpayers have a way of getting stuck with the bill when non-belted
parents die and leave the state to care for the orphans or get turned into
vegetables in an accident they could have walked away from.

If you can guaranteee that you or your insurer will pay for all the medical
costs incurred as a result of your not belting up or that you'll voluntarily
forgo the care and die quietly if you can't pay for it, then I guess I could
get behind that mentality all the way. Of course, you may have trouble
finding an insurer that will underwrite you.

If not, the existing seatbelt laws strikes me as a valid tradeoff between
intruding on your ability to make choices and protecting the rest of us from
the financial fallout of your choices.
